<br>
Do I believe that Complete Heal is flawed? <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yes</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Name another spell in the game that, if removed, would essentially break EQ.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I'm impressed that VI was able to create encounters where CH isn't used in the same old way. Encounters where everyone has a more active role. Mobs that require teamwork and skill to take down. I'm glad that people like Ammelen and Baldrik can enjoy encounters where the guild with better tactics/skills can kill a mob, where a guild with just more members cannot.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> As wizards gain levels, their nukes get bigger. As tanks gain levels, their ac/hp increase. Rogue/monk/ranger/etc dps increases with level. Mages get better pets. etc etc. Clerics get better heals as they level. Some people just see that they are casting the same spell, but that spell gets a lot better as they level up. So wizard upgrades are very direct, cleric upgrades involve the upgrading of the melees they heal, but an upgrade is still an upgrade.<br>
<br>
--Ammelen<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Can you think of any other spell that starts off at roughly a 4-to-1 effect-to-mana ratio (1600 hp for 400 mana) and becomes a 25-to-1 ratio (10000 hps for 400 mana) at the end? That is why I think CH is flawed. Any DDs that increase in effectiveness at such a scale? Also, since I'm too lazy to find out on my own, pre-manaburn, what was the most damage that a single nuke could do?<br>
 <p><br>
--[Rurouni] Tenken (Half Elf)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uvaclavromanov.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vaclav Romanov</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 937<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/10/02 6:49:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3124.topic&index=62>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> Already in this thread you can see the basics of humanity at work...<br>
<br>
I personally was one of the people that started up the entire conversation on the FoH board regarding how ridiculously borked CH has become over the years - relatively speaking everything in EQ skillwise, equipment wise, spellwise - is eclipsed by something else in some regard. This is an important part of the game known as CHARACTER DEVELOPMENT. (if any of you are currently in college and planning to go into game development remember those words - they're really important, trust me) <br>
<br>
Whereas with a Warrior or a Wizard you will acquire a new weapon or spell or whatever to improve upon your character, the cleric class stays relatively stagnant once CH becomes efficient(around level 50 or so w/ today's equipment) - new buff here and there and better &quot;secondary&quot; heals. <br>
<br>
How would you feel as a Wizard, if Manaburn was a vendor spell that you got at level 39 and cost 400 mana w/ a 10 sec cast time and no recast delay(and fundamentally the same otherwise - damage the same as current so as to overshadow all other spells)?<br>
<br>
That is EXACTLY what CH is to a cleric... it's like Ding! Woohoo, 51, I can scribe Remedy finally so I can spot heal better when I screw up and wait too long to CH... Or wow, a new piece of gear that is 1/10th of a CH upgrade to my old gear. (and yes, I said that exact thing a few times ^_^)<br>
<br>
Is it too late to fix? More than likely... with so much being balanced based on it there would be months of retuning lots of content, doesn't mean they couldn't do blanket changes to mob damage output/mana etc. - In XP and raid situations both, of course - but most likely it would be a financial mistake for VI to do at this point. (Most people fear change, even for the better)<br>
<br>
What CH should have been if they hadn't been lazy when they were coding it in the first place is a spell with a scaling mana cost based on the amount it heals(simplest coding method probably being mana cost based on the level of the target)<br>
<br>
And Pigboy/Haels and anyone else who thinks CH Chains are difficult in the slightest (And I mean to do from the standpoint of an individual cleric, not to figure out the appropriate interval for a mobs damage output and latency - that certainly takes a level of skill to determine), I'd really recommend trying out another class all the cleric class boils down to is timing and efficiency - if you can't handle one of the two fundamentals you're a shitty ass cleric.<br>
<br>
<br>
And for those that can't imagine an EQ w/o CH, imagine all these things that could have existed since they currently can't due to CH trivializing them.<br>
<br>
1. Much Higher AC cap.<br>
Nothing quite like the farce which is monk tanking v. warrior tanking - pretty much the same mitigation and significantly higher avoidance for monks - if only they had a few more HP and some form of a taunt skill they could just scrap the warrior class all together.<br>
<br>
2. Less ridiculous Mob Damage Output.<br>
Sure extended encounters are fun so the HP/AC could stay relatively high(although in some cases, the AC is obviously a &quot;tad&quot; overboard), but where is the fun in being a nonmelee annoying a mob for ONE ROUND and dying. Dying isn't fun - Doing the same thing precisely the same way everytime gets boring. (Catch-22 anyone?)<br>
<br>
Hell, I could prolly think of even more stuff, but I'm growing tired of typing this... so this will draw to a close here... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ukassarastilfyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kassara Stilfyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/10/02 8:06:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3124.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Honestly, there is no game there. Fights have been broken down into mathimatical formulas where there is NO actual need for thought.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Course, after you do something over and over again, anything becomes routine.  It took EA 5 shots before we finally killed Aaryonar the first time.  Now he's dropping like Fippy, and yes, it's starting to feel routine.  There's no way around that.  Learn a mob, learn a routine.  If mob dies, routine is successful, repeat next time.<br>
<br>
Whether or not the mob requires a Cheal chain or a spamming of spot heals, when the routine is figured out, that's what you're gonna use.<br>
<br>
This would happen whether or not cheal was in the game.  Once you learn how to beat a mob, once you learn the timing, the resists, the debuffs, the whatevers... it'd become routine.<br>
<br>
Cheal just makes a convienent target.  Perhaps the only *reasonable* argument I've heard is that clerics dont' get heal upgrades.  (1000hp, 2000hp, 3000hp...).  Verant would still make mobs around the spells.  Now that warriors have defensive, VI makes mobs around that.  VI has stated that FD has got abused.  Monks shouldnt' pull.  Yet they've designed encounters that basically require breaking.<br>
<br>
It boils down simply to the fact that players are more clever than any team of designers.  I remember reading an article about the old days of text based muds and one of the main upgrades to one game in it's early days was the addition of an axe as a new weapon.  The playerbase was thrilled, and went out to look for trees to cut down, but none of the designers ever put in a tree.<br>
<br>
Is it our fault it's flawed now?  Or is it Verant's?<br>
<br>
Makes ya wonder...<br>
<br>
Well...makes me wonder at least  (-8<br>
