<br>
No, cheal doesn't limit what Verant can do, the design of the game limits what Verant can do.  EQ was not designed to have the depth of injury you crave.  Cheal is completely incidental to this.  More diverse injuries could be added if they really wanted to, and cheal isn't stopping them -- in fact, it could be their path away from cheal dominance in raid situations.<br>
<br>
There are different types of injuries and cures though: poison, disease, curses, stamina loss, and of course typical hp loss.<br>
<br>
There are more diverse heals in EQ too, away from the cures to the above, you have regens and heals over time which are widely used in the game.  Let's not forget necro healing. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I don't see popular mmorpg's giving you the diversity you like, though.  Complicating healing more will not go well with the masses, and really, a wider range of heals would just add tedium in my opinion -- this is why we don't see more variety in EQ.<br>
<br>
Vac,<br>
<br>
FPS gaming requires more than mouse skill.  Dexterity is helpful, but so is quick thinking and on-the-fly strategy.  This was especially true in teamplay FPS gaming like Team Fortress where strategy and teamwork were paramount.  Even mere deathmatches in Quake and other FPS's rely heavily in strategy in the high end gaming scenes -- with a prerequisite of dexterity.<br>
<br>
Strategies are needed and used in EQ, but their value is diminished because information is so quickly disseminated.  If you complicate things, the masses will follow the most effective paths found by only a few.<br>
<br>
We take a lot for granted in EQ.  The way the modern game is played today was not obvious to people right away, but is accepted as such now.  It has evolved dramatically, and as they've slowed the single group gameplay down, the game has become more accessable and much more tedious.  EQ was fun when you were on your toes throughout a night, when mana was low and keeping everyone alive was really tough..  or when you had to make a hard choice on an over-pull and know that someone had to die, and you had to make the choice who.  <br>
<br>
That's gone now, and it sucks.  And no, before someone says that's because of cheal, it's not.  It's because the game has been made easier by countless class, weapon, equipment, spell and skill upgrades, especially through expansion.  However, while they made equipment better in each expansion, they kept the mob difficulty the same, trivializing encounters.  Cheal has been upgraded with equipment, yes, by it's nature, but it's not the cause of the problem, just part of it.  Characters have been upgraded vastly, while mobs have not.  Players know the game better than ever and the AI is mostly unchanged. <br>
<br>
I don't know when mmorpg AI will see significant improvements, simply because of server  constraints.  EQ servers are already powered by server farms.  Increasing AI to that of even something like Half-Life is currently impractical -- servers would need way too much memory, internal bandwidth, processing power to be cost effective.<br>
<br>
In the future, when advanced RTS AI can be implemented on an MMOG scale, then you'll see more interesting encounters.  That's probably 4th gen though. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/utenkenofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tenken of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 681<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/11/02 4:52:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3124.topic&index=77>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hawaii.rr.com/kcsystems/ten/domo.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> MMORPG Generations</span><hr size=1> Well, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.legendmud.org/raph/index.html">Raph Koster</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, Creative Director on <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://starwarsgalaxies.station.sony.com/">Star Wars Galaxies</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, we are in the 3rd generation of MMORPGS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/starwars/Forum3/HTML/066666.html">boards.station.sony.com/ubb/starwars/Forum3/HTML/066666.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> All of the games you cited are still 1st gen &quot;massively multiplayer&quot; games, and they're maybe 3rd gen online worlds. There's some debate about what the generations really are, but I'd break it up this way:<br>
1st gen: the original MUD and its kin. Item collecting scavenger hunts, text-based, based around gaming systems. Starts around in 1978.<br>
<br>
Some commentators, such as Jessica Mulligan, insert a generation here for the many games that thrived on the pay networks such as GEnie. A lot of these games were significantly distinct from muds.<br>
<br>
2nd gen: social games which allowed player creativity. These kick in slightly in 1985 with Habitat (which was graphical) but really hit in 1989-1992 with MUSHes and MOOs.<br>
<br>
3rd gen: graphical takes on design retreads of 1st gen games. 1995-6 is when these started out in development, and the first out was Meridian 59 in '96. We're still in this generation.<br>
<br>
4th gen: will probably recapitulate the development of player-contributed content, and will focus, I think, on better service, and distributed worlds. You probably have five+ years to wait.<br>
<br>
-Raph Koster<br>
Creative Director<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Click on the link to Raph's site. Some very interesting stuff there on MMORPG development, history, and maintaining communities.<br>
 <p><br>
--[Rurouni] Tenken (Half Elf)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ukassarastilfyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kassara Stilfyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/11/02 8:15:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3124.topic&index=78>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: MMORPG Generations</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  That's gone now, and it sucks. And no, before someone says that's because of cheal, it's not. It's because the game has been made easier by countless class, weapon, equipment, spell and skill upgrades, especially through expansion. However, while they made equipment better in each expansion, they kept the mob difficulty the same, trivializing encounters.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Obviously with every expansion the previous world gets trivialized.  It's simply how these games work.  Normal in Diablo 2 is trivialized when you hit Nightmare.  Now we're posed with the problem of simply adding material.<br>
<br>
This, of course, has it's pros and cons.  You can't really add stuff without making existing stuff trivial, but you can't have a static world either.  Which is worse?<br>
<br>
In my book, having things static.  With new gear, we've been able to have more sporatic groups.  Back in the days of pre-velious Kunark, you'd never consider having a monk tank in a seb group.  You'd need the holy trinity (war/enc/clr), with a shaman, monk and wizard/druid or whatever probably simply because the mobs demanded it.<br>
<br>
Now, though, we can diversify more.  Have classes tank that normally couldn't.  Not rely on finding those elusive chanters free for a group cause every dungeon xp group required one.  Is this a bad thing?  Depends on personal perspective.  I'd say no.  It lets people group more in dangerous places with non-standard groups with a reasonable chance of survival.  Sure, it cuts down on the adrenaline rushes, but maybe that's because you're not finding the right places to fight in.<br>
<br>
There's only so many things you can give an NPC before you have to just give up and throw more AC/HP/SV on it, that's hardware limitations.<br>
<br>
And another point, you can't really overhaul the entire world with every release.  When PoP comes out, VI can't really say &quot;Well, now we've really trivialized Trakanon, let's give him 100khp, rampage, balance and a mana drain&quot;.  But they can't really go &quot;Hmm...let's make the Tribunal unbeatable so it won't be a trivial fight until the next expansion&quot; either.<br>
<br>
Sure, it's always fun to think about the good old days, but there's no way to go back.  All you can do now is try to find new spots to relive them.<br>
